{"ts":1769775311123,"data":[{"idPlayer":"34202780","idTeam":"134294","idTeam2":null,"idTeamNational":null,"idAPIfootball":null,"idPlayerManager":null,"idWikidata":null,"idTransferMkt":null,"idESPN":null,"strNationality":"Brazil","strPlayer":"Adenor Leonardo Bacchi","strPlayerAlternate":"Tite","strTeam":"Cruzeiro","strTeam2":"","strSport":"Soccer","intSoccerXMLTeamID":null,"dateBorn":"1961-05-25","dateDied":null,"strNumber":"","dateSigned":null,"strSigning":"","strWage":"","strOutfitter":"","strKit":"","strAgent":"","strBirthLocation":"Caxias do Sul, Brazil","strEthnicity":"Hispanic","strStatus":"Coaching","strDescriptionEN":"Adenor Leonardo Bacchi (born 25 May 1961), commonly known as Tite, is a Brazilian professional football coach and former player who was the head coach of the Brazil national team from 2016 to 2022.\r\n\r\nTite played from 1978 to 1984 for Caxias, then a season for Esportivo de Bento Gonçalves and a season for Portuguesa. The three following seasons from 1986 to 1989 at Guarani were his most successful as player. At age 27, he ended his career due to successive knee injuries that caused him to lose mobility in one of his knees.\r\n\r\nFrom 1991 onwards, Tite coached more than 10 teams in more than 15 stints. Amongst these were his first club, Caxias that he returned to in 1999, and they won the 2000 Campeonato Gaúcho defeating Grêmio, which had Ronaldinho in its team. Due to the achievements with Caxias, Tite became the Grêmio coach in 2001 where they won the 2001 Campeonato Gaúcho and the 2001 Copa do Brasil. He stayed until 2003 when Tite trained other teams: São Caetano, Corinthians in 2004, Atlético Mineiro in 2005, Palmeiras in 2006, and Al Ain of the United Arab Emirates in 2007. From 2008 to 2009 he trained Internacional and they won the 2008 Copa Sudamericana and the 2009 Campeonato Gaúcho. At the end of 2010 he was announced as a coach of Al Wahda of the United Arab Emirates, but he left the club months later to return to Corinthians.\r\n\r\nFor Corinthians, Tite won the 2011 Campeonato Brasileiro Série A title, the 2012 Copa Libertadores title, the 2012 FIFA Club World Cup title against Chelsea, the 2013 Campeonato Paulista and the 2013 Recopa Sudamericana. On 14 November 2013, Tite announced that he was leaving the club. After a sabbatical period, Tite returned to Corinthians in 2015, where they won the 2015 Campeonato Brasileiro Série A.","strDescriptionDE":null,"strDescriptionFR":null,"strDescriptionCN":null,"strDescriptionIT":null,"strDescriptionJP":null,"strDescriptionRU":null,"strDescriptionES":null,"strDescriptionPT":null,"strDescriptionSE":null,"strDescriptionNL":null,"strDescriptionHU":null,"strDescriptionNO":null,"strDescriptionIL":null,"strDescriptionPL":null,"strGender":"Male","strSide":"","strPosition":"Manager","strCollege":null,"strFacebook":"","strWebsite":"","strTwitter":"","strInstagram":"","strYoutube":"","strHeight":"1.80 m (5 ft 11 in)","strWeight":"","intLoved":"0","strThumb":"https://r2.thesportsdb.com/images/media/player/thumb/heb1gr1668792652.jpg","strPoster":null,"strCutout":null,"strCartoon":null,"strRender":null,"strBanner":null,"strFanart1":null,"strFanart2":null,"strFanart3":null,"strFanart4":null,"strCreativeCommons":"No","strLocked":"unlocked","strLastName":"Bacchi"},{"idPlayer":"34152858","idTeam":"134294","idTeam2":null,"idTeamNational":null,"idAPIfootball":"44348","idPlayerManager":null,"idWikidata":null,"idTransferMkt":null,"idESPN":"174782","strNationality":"Brazil","strPlayer":"Carlos Eduardo","strPlayerAlternate":"Carlos Eduardo de Oliveira Alves","strTeam":"Cruzeiro","strTeam2":"","strSport":"Soccer","intSoccerXMLTeamID":"129","dateBorn":"1989-10-17","dateDied":null,"strNumber":"21","dateSigned":"2014-09-12","strSigning":"","strWage":"","strOutfitter":"","strKit":"","strAgent":"","strBirthLocation":"Ribeirão Preto, Brazil","strEthnicity":"Hispanic","strStatus":"Active","strDescriptionEN":"Carlos Eduardo de Oliveira Alves (born 17 October 1989), known as Carlos Eduardo, is a Brazilian professional footballer who plays for Cruzeiro as a midfielder.","strDescriptionDE":null,"strDescriptionFR":"Carlos Eduardo de Oliveira Alves, plus connu sous le nom de Carlos Eduardo (né le 17 octobre 1989 à Ribeirão Preto dans l'État de São Paulo) est un footballeur brésilien qui évolue comme milieu offensif.\r\n\r\nIl joue actuellement avec l'OGC Nice, en prêt du FC Porto.","strDescriptionCN":null,"strDescriptionIT":null,"strDescriptionJP":null,"strDescriptionRU":null,"strDescriptionES":null,"strDescriptionPT":null,"strDescriptionSE":null,"strDescriptionNL":null,"strDescriptionHU":null,"strDescriptionNO":null,"strDescriptionIL":null,"strDescriptionPL":null,"strGender":"Male","strSide":"Right","strPosition":"Attacking Midfield","strCollege":null,"strFacebook":"","strWebsite":"","strTwitter":"","strInstagram":"","strYoutube":"","strHeight":"184 cm","strWeight":"172 lbs","intLoved":"0","strThumb":"https://r2.thesportsdb.com/images/media/player/thumb/0enuew1733024497.jpg","strPoster":null,"strCutout":"https://r2.thesportsdb.com/images/media/player/cutout/qfi65x1767455734.png","strCartoon":null,"strRender":null,"strBanner":null,"strFanart1":null,"strFanart2":null,"strFanart3":null,"strFanart4":null,"strCreativeCommons":"No","strLocked":"unlocked","strLastName":"Eduardo"},{"idPlayer":"34167639","idTeam":"134294","idTeam2":null,"idTeamNational":null,"idAPIfootball":"10229","idPlayerManager":null,"idWikidata":null,"idTransferMkt":null,"idESPN":null,"strNationality":"Brazil","strPlayer":"Cássio","strPlayerAlternate":"Cássio Roberto Ramos","strTeam":"Cruzeiro","strTeam2":"","strSport":"Soccer","intSoccerXMLTeamID":null,"dateBorn":"1987-06-06","dateDied":null,"strNumber":"1","dateSigned":null,"strSigning":"","strWage":"","strOutfitter":"","strKit":"Nike Phantom VSN","strAgent":"","strBirthLocation":"Veranópolis, Brazil","strEthnicity":"Hispanic","strStatus":"Active","strDescriptionEN":"Cássio Roberto Ramos (born 6 June 1987), simply known as Cássio, is a Brazilian professional footballer who plays as a goalkeeper for Cruzeiro.\r\n\r\nCássio began his career at the academy of Grêmio in his home state of Rio Grande do Sul and was quickly promoted to the club's first team. He then spent some time in the Netherlands for PSV, where he won two trophies, and Sparta Rotterdam, before joining Corinthians in 2012.\r\n\r\nUntil his departure for Cruzeiro in May 2024, Cássio has made over 700 appearances for Corinthians and won two Brasileirão titles, four Campeonato Paulista titles, a Copa Libertadores, a Recopa Sudamericana and a FIFA Club World Cup in 2012, where the Timão beat Chelsea in the final. Cássio himself was named man of the match and also awarded the tournament's Golden Ball. Since 2019, he is Corinthians' most decorated player in their history.\r\n\r\nCássio was a Brazilian international from 2007 to 2019 and played at two major tournaments, the 2018 FIFA World Cup and the 2019 Copa América, which Brazil won.","strDescriptionDE":null,"strDescriptionFR":null,"strDescriptionCN":null,"strDescriptionIT":null,"strDescriptionJP":null,"strDescriptionRU":null,"strDescriptionES":null,"strDescriptionPT":null,"strDescriptionSE":null,"strDescriptionNL":null,"strDescriptionHU":null,"strDescriptionNO":null,"strDescriptionIL":null,"strDescriptionPL":null,"strGender":"Male","strSide":"Right","strPosition":"Goalkeeper","strCollege":null,"strFacebook":"","strWebsite":"","strTwitter":"","strInstagram":"","strYoutube":"","strHeight":"1.96 m (6 ft 5 in)","strWeight":"92 kg","intLoved":"0","strThumb":"https://r2.thesportsdb.com/images/media/player/thumb/t4skpl1562597186.jpg","strPoster":null,"strCutout":"https://r2.thesportsdb.com/images/media/player/cutout/cta4jv1767453871.png","strCartoon":null,"strRender":null,"strBanner":null,"strFanart1":null,"strFanart2":null,"strFanart3":null,"strFanart4":null,"strCreativeCommons":"No","strLocked":"unlocked","strLastName":"Cássio"},{"idPlayer":"34219661","idTeam":"134294","idTeam2":null